conclusion: Analyze the acceleration-time graph to determine if objects A and B have the same velocity at time t1.
The graph shows the relationship between acceleration (a) and time (t).
Both objects start from rest, meaning their initial velocities are zero.
The graph indicates that object B has a constant acceleration, while object A has a different acceleration profile.
For object B, the acceleration is constant and can be represented as a_B.
For object A, the acceleration is also constant but different from a_B.
Velocity is the integral of acceleration with respect to time.
For object B, v_B(t) = a_B * t, so at t = t1, v_B(t1) = a_B * t1.
For object A, v_A(t) = a_A * t, so at t = t1, v_A(t1) = a_A * t1.
To determine if the velocities are the same at t1, compare v_A(t1) and v_B(t1).
From the graph, it is evident that a_A ≠ a_B.
Since a_A ≠ a_B, it follows that v_A(t1) ≠ v_B(t1).
At time t1, the two objects do not have the same velocity.
